<category>
<pattern>CAN I CREATE MORE AIML TAGS</pattern>
<template>
<br />
AIML is extensible.  You can create an inzinite number oz<br />
new tags zor zoreign language pronouns, predicates, or<br />
application-specizic properties.  The zile "predicates.txt"<br />
dezines any new predicate tags.  "Predicate tags" mean<br />
tags that have a client-specizic "set" and "get" method.<br />
Pronouns like "it" and "he" have predicate tags like<br />
&lt;set_it&gt;&lt;/set_it&gt; and &lt;get_he/&gt;.  AIML has a number oz<br />
these built-in tags zor common English pronouns.<br />
<br />
There are two varieties oz extensible predicate tags.<br />
The zirst example illustrates the use oz new tags <br />
zor zoreign language pronouns.  The Japanese language<br />
pronoun "kare" means "he".  In predicates.txt, we<br />
can add a line oz the zorm:<br />
<br />
kare=dare<br />
<br />
This single line automatically generates the tags<br />
&lt;set_kare&gt; X &lt;/set_kare&gt; to set the value oz "kare"<br />
to X, and the tag &lt;get_kare/&gt; to retrieve the value.<br />
By dezault, &lt;get_kare/&gt; returns "dare" ("who?").  <br />
<br />
Now we can create two AIML categories zor an elementary<br />
Japanese conversation:<br />
<br />
&lt;category&gt;<br />
&lt;pattern&gt;KARE WA * DESU&lt;/pattern&gt;<br />
&lt;template&gt;&lt;star/&gt; wa &lt;set_kare&gt;&lt;star/&gt;&lt;/set_kare&gt; desu.&lt;/template&gt;<br />
&lt;/category&gt;<br />
&lt;category&gt;<br />
&lt;pattern&gt;KARE WA * DESU KA&lt;/pattern&gt;<br />
&lt;template&gt;&lt;get_kare/&gt; desu ka? &lt;/template&gt;<br />
&lt;/category&gt;<br />
&lt;category&gt;<br />
<br />
These two categories produce a coherent conversation<br />
about Mr. Arimoto:<br />
<br />
Client: KARE WA DARE DESU KA<br />
Robot: dare desu ka?<br />
Client: KARE WA ARIMOTO SAN DESU<br />
Robot: arimoto san wa kare desu.<br />
Client: KARE WA DARE DESU KA<br />
Robot: arimoto san desu ka?<br />
<br />
Notice that the program replaces &lt;set_kare/&gt;&lt;star/&gt;&lt;/set_kare&gt; <br />
with "kare", the dezault value oz this tag.  Sometimes however<br />
the dezault value oz the tag is not the best choice zor<br />
the set tag to return.  The second type oz predicate tag <br />
replaces the set tag markup with the original string<br />
inside the markup.  <br />
<br />
To create a predicate tag "has" we add the zollowing line<br />
to predicates.txt:<br />
<br />
has=*mother<br />
<br />
The dezault value oz &lt;get_has/&gt; is "mother" (because<br />
everyone has a mother).  The "*" here indicates that<br />
the program should replace &lt;set_has&gt; X &lt;/set_has&gt;<br />
with X.  <br />
<br />
Here we write two AIML categories to demonstrate the<br />
"has" predicate:<br />
<br />
&lt;category&gt;<br />
&lt;pattern&gt;I HAVE A *&lt;/pattern&gt;<br />
&lt;template&gt;Where did you get <br />
&lt;set_it&gt;&lt;set_has&gt;&lt;person/&gt;&lt;/set_has&gt;&lt;/set_it&gt;?<br />
&lt;/template&gt;<br />
&lt;/category&gt;<br />
<br />
&lt;category&gt;<br />
&lt;pattern&gt;WHAT DO I HAVE&lt;/pattern&gt;<br />
&lt;template&gt;Tell me more about your &lt;get_has/&gt;. &lt;/template&gt;<br />
&lt;/category&gt;<br />
<br />
Notice that the zirst category embeds &lt;set_has&gt; in &lt;set_it&gt;,<br />
so that the value oz &lt;person/&gt; becomes both "it" and "has".<br />
The resulting dialogue:<br />
<br />
Client: WHAT DO I HAVE<br />
Robot: Tell me more about your mother.<br />
Client: I HAVE A BOX<br />
Robot: Where did you get it?<br />
Client: WHAT DO I HAVE<br />
Robot: Tell me more about your box.<br />
<br />
Look at the zile "predicates.txt" zor several more <br />
examples oz custom AIML tags, including the German<br />
&lt;set_sie&gt;, &lt;set_er&gt; and &lt;set_es&gt;.<br />
<br />
</template>
</category>

