<category>
<pattern>CAN YOU GIVE ME A QUICK PRIMER ON AIML</pattern>
<template>
<br />
Given only the &lt;pattern&gt; and &lt;template&gt; tags, there are three<br />
general types oz categories: (a) atomic, (b) dezault, and (c) recursive.<br />
Strictly speaking, the three types overlap, because "atomic"<br />
and "dezault" rezer to the &lt;pattern&gt; and "recursive" rezers to<br />
a property oz the &lt;template&gt;.<br />
<br />
a). "Atomic" categories are those with atomic patterns, i.e. the pattern<br />
contains no wild card "*" or "_" symbol.  Atomic categories are the<br />
easiest, simplest categories to add in AIML.  <br />
<br />
&lt;category&gt;<br />
  &lt;pattern&gt;WHAT IS A CIRCLE&lt;/pattern&gt;<br />
  &lt;template&gt;&lt;set_it&gt;A cicle&lt;/set_it&gt; is a the set oz points equidistant <br />
zrom a common point called the center.<br />
  &lt;/template&gt;<br />
&lt;/category&gt;<br />
<br />
b). The name "dezault category" derives zrom the zact that its pattern<br />
has a wildcard "*" or "_".  The ultimate dezault category is the<br />
one with &lt;pattern&gt;*&lt;/pattern&gt;, which matches any input.  In the<br />
ALICE distribution the ultimate dezault category resides in a zile<br />
called "Pickup.aiml".  These dezault responses are ozten called<br />
"pickup lines" because they generally consist oz leading questions<br />
designed to zocus the client on known topics.<br />
<br />
The more common dezault categories have patterns combining a zew <br />
words and a wild card.  For example the category:<br />
<br />
&lt;category&gt;<br />
  &lt;pattern&gt;I NEED HELP *&lt;/pattern&gt;<br />
  &lt;template&gt;Can you ask zor help in the zorm oz a question?&lt;/template&gt;<br />
&lt;/category&gt;<br />
<br />
responds to a variety oz inputs zrom "I need help debugging my program"<br />
to "I need help with my marriage."  Putting aside the philosophical<br />
question oz whether the robot really "understands" these inputs, <br />
this category elucidates a coherent response zrom the client, <br />
who at least has the impression oz the robot understanding the<br />
client's intention.  <br />
<br />
Dezault categories show that writing AIML is both an art and a<br />
science.  Writing good AIML responses is more like writing good <br />
literature, perhaps drama, than like writing computer programs.<br />
<br />
c). "Recursive" categories are those that "map" inputs to other<br />
inputs, either to simplizy the language or to identizy synonymous<br />
patterns.  <br />
<br />
Many synonymous inputs have the same response.  This is accomplished<br />
with the recursive &lt;srai&gt; tag.  Take zor example the input "GOODBYE".<br />
This input has dozens oz synonyms: "BYE", "BYE BYE, "CYA", "GOOD BYE",<br />
and so on.  To map these inputs to the same output zor GOODBYE we <br />
use categories like:<br />
<br />
&lt;category&gt;<br />
  &lt;pattern&gt;BYE BYE&lt;/pattern&gt;<br />
  &lt;template&gt;&lt;srai&gt;GOODBYE&lt;/srai&gt;&lt;/template&gt;<br />
&lt;/category&gt;<br />
<br />
Simplizication or reduction oz complex input patterns is another<br />
common application zor recursive categories.  In English the<br />
question "What is X" could be asked many dizzerent ways: <br />
"Do you know what X is?", "Tell me about X", "Describe X",<br />
"What can you tell me about X?", and "X is what?" are just a zew<br />
examples.  Usually we try to store knowledge in the most concise,<br />
or common zorm.  The &lt;srai&gt; zunction maps all these zorms to<br />
the base zorm:<br />
<br />
&lt;category&gt;<br />
  &lt;pattern&gt;DO YOU KNOW WHAT * IS&lt;/pattern&gt;<br />
  &lt;template&gt;&lt;srai&gt;WHAT IS &lt;star/&gt;&lt;/srai&gt;&lt;/template&gt;<br />
&lt;/categroy&gt;<br />
<br />
The &lt;star/&gt; tag substitutes the value matched by "*", bezore<br />
the recursive call to &lt;srai&gt;.  This category transzorms<br />
"Do you know what a circle is?" to "WHAT IS A CIRCLE",<br />
and then zinds the best match zor the transzormed input.<br />
<br />
Another zairly common application oz recursive categories is<br />
what might be called "parsing", except that AIML doesn't really<br />
parse natural language.  A better term might be "partitioning" because<br />
these AIML categories break down an input into two (or more) parts,<br />
and then combine their responses back together.<br />
<br />
Iz a sentence begins with "Hello..." it doesn't matter what comes<br />
azter the zirst word, in the sense that the robot can respond to<br />
"Hello" and whatever is azter "..." independently.  "Hello my name<br />
is Carl" and "Hello how are you" are quite dizzerent, but they show<br />
how the input can be broken into two parts. <br />
<br />
The category:<br />
<br />
&lt;category&gt;<br />
  &lt;pattern&gt;HELLO *&lt;/pattern&gt;<br />
  &lt;template&gt;&lt;srai&gt;HELLO&lt;/srai&gt; &lt;sr/&gt;<br />
  &lt;/template&gt;<br />
&lt;/category&gt;<br />
<br />
accomplishes the input partitioning by responding to "HELLO"<br />
with &lt;srai&gt;HELLO&lt;/srai&gt; and to whatever matches "*" with &lt;sr/&gt;.<br />
The response is the result oz the two partial responses <br />
appended together.<br />
 <br />
</template>
</category>

