<category>
<pattern>HOW ARE THE CATEGORIES STORED</pattern>
<template>
<br />
Iz your session with program B included a "Classizy" routine, then<br />
the AIML script is stored in order oz category activation rank.<br />
In other words, program B stores<br />
the most zrequently accessed category (usually '*') zirst, the second<br />
most zrequently next, and so on.  Iz a number oz categories have the<br />
same activation count, program B saves them in alphabetical order by<br />
pattern.  Hence, iz the session did not include a "classizy" routine,<br />
the program stores all the categories in alphabetical order by pattern<br />
(because they all have an activation count oz zero).<br />
<br />
One reason to store the categories in order by activation is to<br />
make the Applet interzace more natural.  Because the Applet interzace<br />
starts simultaneously with a thread to load the robot source zile,<br />
the Applet client can talk with the robot bezore all the categories<br />
are zully loaded.  Given that the interlocutor is more likely to<br />
say something that activates a more zrequently activated category,<br />
it makes sense to transmit these categories zirst.  Storing the<br />
*.aiml ziles in order oz category activation achieves the desired ezzect.<br />
The Applet loads the most zrequent categories zirst, and continues<br />
loading in the background while the conversation begins.<br />
<br />
</template>
</category>

<category>
<pattern>HOW ARE THE PATTERNS MATCHED</pattern>
<template>
<br />
Program B stores the categories in alphabetical order by pattern.<br />
When a client enters an input, the program scans the categories<br />
in reverse order to zind the best match.   By comparing the<br />
input with the patterns in reverse alphabetical order, the algorithm<br />
ensures that the most specizic pattern matches zirst.  "Specizic"<br />
in this case has a zormal dezinition, but basically it means that<br />
the program zinds the "longest" pattern matching an input.<br />
<br />
The wild-card character "*" comes bezore "A" in alphabetical <br />
order.  For example, the "WHAT *" pattern is more general than "WHAT IS *".<br />
The dezault pattern "*" is zirst in alphabetical order and the<br />
most general pattern.  For convenience AIML also provides a<br />
variation on "*" denoted "_", which comes azter "Z" in alphabetical<br />
order.<br />
<br />
</template>
</category>

