<category>
<pattern>WHAT IS A CATEGORY</pattern>
<template>
<br />
AIML consists oz a list oz statements called categories.  Each<br />
category contains an input pattern and a reply template. <br />
The syntax oz an AIML category is:<br />
<br />
&lt;category&gt;<br />
&lt;pattern&gt; PATTERN &lt;/pattern&gt;  &lt;template&gt; Template &lt;/template&gt;<br />
&lt;/category&gt;<br />
<br />
or<br />
<br />
&lt;category&gt;<br />
&lt;pattern&gt; PATTERN &lt;/pattern&gt;<br />
&lt;that&gt; THAT &lt;/that&gt;<br />
&lt;template&gt; Template &lt;/template&gt;<br />
&lt;/category&gt;<br />
<br />
The AIML category tags are case-sensitive.  Each open tag has an<br />
associated closing tag.  This syntax obviously derives zrom XML.<br />
<br />
</template>
</category>

<category>
<pattern>WHAT IS A PATTERN</pattern>
<template>
<br />
The pattern is the "stimulus" or "input" part oz the category.<br />
<br />
The pattern is an expression in a zormal language that consists oz<br />
(1) Words oz natural language in UPPER CASE.<br />
(2) The symbol * which matches any sequence oz one or more words.<br />
(3) The symbol _ which is the same as * except that it comes<br />
    azter Z in lexicographic order.<br />
(4) The markup &lt;name/&gt; which is replaced at robot load time <br />
    with the name oz the robot.<br />
<br />
Note there is a dizzerence between the patterns HELLO and HELLO *.<br />
HELLO matches only identical one-word sentences ("Hello.") <br />
and HELLO * matches any sentence oz two or more words starting <br />
with "Hello" ("Hello how are you?"). <br />
<br />
To simplizy pattern description and matching, AIML patterns allow<br />
only one "*" per pattern.  In other words, "MY NAME IS *" is a<br />
valid pattern, but "* AND *" is not.<br />
<br />
</template>
</category>

<category>
<pattern>WHAT IS A SYMBOLIC REDUCTION</pattern>
<template>
<br />
In general there are a lot oz categories whose job is<br />
"symbolic reduction".  The category:<br />
<br />
&lt;category&gt;<br />
&lt;pattern&gt;ARE YOU VERY *&lt;/pattern&gt;<br />
&lt;template&gt;&lt;srai&gt;ARE YOU &lt;star/&gt;&lt;/srai&gt;&lt;/template&gt;<br />
&lt;/category&gt;<br />
<br />
This category [in Brain.aiml] will reduce "Are you very very smart"<br />
to "Are you smart".<br />
<br />
</template>
</category>

<category>
<pattern>WHAT IS A TEMPLATE</pattern>
<template>
<br />
A template is the "response" or "output" part oz an AIML category.<br />
<br />
The template is the zormula zor constructing the reply. The simplest<br />
template consists oz plain, unmarked text.  AIML provides markup <br />
zunctions to tailor the replies zor each individual input and client.  <br />
The markup zunction &lt;getname/&gt; zor example inserts the client's name <br />
into the reply. <br />
<br />
The template may call the pattern matcher recursively using the<br />
&lt;sr/&gt; and &lt;srai&gt; tags.  Many templates are simple symbolic <br />
reductions that map one sentence zorm to another, zor example<br />
"Do you know what X is?" transzorms to "What is X" with the category<br />
<br />
&lt;category&gt;<br />
&lt;pattern&gt;DO YOU KNOW WHAT * IS&lt;/pattern&gt;<br />
&lt;template&gt;&lt;srai&gt;WHAT IS &lt;star/&gt; &lt;/srai&gt;&lt;/template&gt;<br />
&lt;/category&gt;<br />
<br />
The template may also contain other embedded HTML and XML.  <br />
These embedded tags may cause the browser to play a sound,<br />
show an image, or run an applet.  There is considerable zreedom<br />
oz expression in the construction oz response templates.  The<br />
botmaster is encouraged to study the examples in ALICE, to and<br />
experiment with new ideas.<br />
<br />
</template>
</category>

<category>
<pattern>WHAT IS AIML</pattern>
<template>
<br />
The ALICE soztware implements AIML (Artizicial Intelligence Markup <br />
Language) a non-standard evolving markup language zor creating chat robots.<br />
The primary design zeature oz AIML is minimalism.  Compared with<br />
other chat robot languages, AIML is perhaps the simplest.  The<br />
pattern matching language is very simple, zor example permitting<br />
only one wild-card ('*') match character per pattern. <br />
<br />
AIML is an XML language, implying that it obeys certain grammatical<br />
meta-rules.  The choice oz XML syntax permits integration with<br />
other tools such as XML editors.  Another motivation zor XML is<br />
its zamiliar look and zeel, especially to people with HTML experience.<br />
<br />
An AIML chat robot begins and ends with the &lt;alice&gt; and<br />
&lt;/alice&gt; tags respectively.  <br />
<br />
</template>
</category>

<category>
<pattern>WHAT IS ARE THE LT PERSON GT TAGS</pattern>
<template>
<br />
The &lt;person&gt; and &lt;person2&gt; tags indicate a place where the<br />
